# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: queueing-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] The **birth–death process** (or **birth-and-death process**) is a special case of continuous-time Markov process where the state transitions are of only two types: "births", which increase the state variable by one and "deaths", which decrease the state by one.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] The model's name comes from a common application, the use of such models to represent the current size of a population where the transitions are literal births and deaths.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] Birth–death processes have many applications in demography, queueing theory, performance engineering, epidemiology, biology and other areas.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] They may be used, for example, to study the evolution of bacteria, the number of people with a disease within a population, or the number of customers in line at the supermarket.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] When a birth occurs, the process goes from state *n* to *n* + 1.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] When a death occurs, the process goes from state *n* to state *n* − 1.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] The process is specified by positive birth rates $\{\lambda _{i}\}_{i=0\dots \infty }$ and positive death rates $\{\mu _{i}\}_{i=1\dots \infty }$ .
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] The number of individuals in the process at time t is denoted by $X(t)$ .
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] The process has the Markov property and $P_{i,j}(t)={\mathsf {P}}\{X(t+s)=j|X(s)=i\}$ describes how $X(t)$ changes through time.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] This process is represented by the following figure with the states of the process (i.e. the number of individuals in the population) depicted by the circles, and transitions between states indicated by the arrows.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] For recurrence and transience in Markov processes see Section 5.3 from Markov chain.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] Conditions for recurrence and transience were established by Samuel Karlin and James McGregor.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] By using the **extended Bertrand's test**, the conditions for recurrence, transience, ergodicity and null-recurrence can be derived in a more explicit form.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] Then, the conditions for recurrence and transience of a birth-and-death process are as follows.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] where the empty sum for $K=1$ is assumed to be 0.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] Wider classes of birth-and-death processes, for which the conditions for recurrence and transience can be established, can be found in.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] Consider one-dimensional random walk $S_{t},\ t=0,1,\ldots ,$ that is defined as follows.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] So, recurrence or transience of the random walk is associated with recurrence or transience of the birth-and-death process.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] where the empty sum for $K=1$ is assumed to be zero.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] In turn, the last system of differential equations is derived from the system of difference equations that describes the dynamic of the system in a small time $\Delta t$ .
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] During this small time $\Delta t$ only three types of transitions are considered as one death, or one birth, or no birth nor death.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] The probability of the first two of these transitions has the order of $\Delta t$ .
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] Other transitions during this small interval $\Delta t$ such as *more than one birth*, or *more than one death*, or *at least one birth and at least one death* have the probabilities that are of smaller order than $\Delta t$ , and hence are negligible in derivations.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] If the system is in state *k*, then the probability of birth during an interval $\Delta t$ is $\lambda _{k}\Delta t+o(\Delta t)$ , the probability of death is $\mu _{k}\Delta t+o(\Delta t)$ , and the probability of no birth and no death is $1-\lambda _{k}\Delta t-\mu _{k}\Delta t+o(\Delta t)$ .
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] For a population process, "birth" is the transition towards increasing the population size by 1 while "death" is the transition towards decreasing the population size by 1.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] A pure birth process is a birth–death process where $\mu _{i}=0$ for all $i\geq 0$ .
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] A **pure death process** is a birth–death process where $\lambda _{i}=0$ for all $i\geq 0$ .
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] Birth–death processes are used in phylodynamics as a prior distribution for phylogenies, i.e. a binary tree in which birth events correspond to branches of the tree and death events correspond to leaf nodes.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] Notably, they are used in viral phylodynamics to understand the transmission process and how the number of people infected changes through time.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] The use of generalized birth-death processes in phylodynamics has stimulated investigations into the degree to which the rates of birth and death can be identified from data.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] While the model is unidentifiable in general, the subset of models that are typically used are identifiable.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] In queueing theory the birth–death process is the most fundamental example of a queueing model, the *M/M/C/K/ $\infty$ /FIFO* (in complete Kendall's notation) queue.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] This is a queue with Poisson arrivals, drawn from an infinite population, and *C* servers with exponentially distributed service times with *K* places in the queue.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] Despite the assumption of an infinite population this model is a good model for various telecommunication systems.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] The **M/M/1** is a single server queue with an infinite buffer size.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] In a non-random environment the birth–death process in queueing models tend to be long-term averages, so the average rate of arrival is given as $\lambda$ and the average service time as $1/\mu$ .
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] Pure birth process with $\lambda _{k}\equiv \lambda$ is a particular case of the M/M/1 queueing process.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] That is, a (homogeneous) Poisson process is a pure birth process.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] The M/M/C is a multi-server queue with *C* servers and an infinite buffer.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] Pure death process with $\mu _{k}=k\mu$ is a particular case of the M/M/C queueing process.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] that presents the version of binomial distribution depending on time parameter t (see Binomial process).
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] The M/M/1/K queue is a single server queue with a buffer of size *K*.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] This queue has applications in telecommunications, as well as in biology when a population has a capacity limit.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] A queue is said to be in equilibrium if the steady state probabilities $\pi _{k}=\lim _{t\to \infty }p_{k}(t),\ k=0,1,\ldots ,$ exist.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] The condition for the existence of these steady-state probabilities in the case of M/M/1 queue is $\rho =\lambda /\mu <1$ and in the case of M/M/C queue is $\rho =\lambda /(C\mu )<1$ .
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] The parameter $\rho$ is usually called load parameter or utilization parameter.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] Sometimes it is also called traffic intensity.
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] Bilateral birth-and-death process is defined similarly to that standard one with the only difference that the birth and death rates $\lambda _{i}$ and $\mu _{i}$ are defined for the values of index parameter $i=0,\pm 1,\pm 2,\ldots$ .
[src:queueing-theory/birth-death-process] The notions of ergodicity and null-recurrence are defined similarly by extending the corresponding notions of the standard birth-and-death process.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The **erlang** (symbol **E**) is a dimensionless unit that is used in telephony as a measure of offered load or carried load on service-providing elements such as telephone circuits or telephone switching equipment.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] A single cord circuit has the capacity to be used for 60 minutes in one hour.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] Full utilization of that capacity, 60 minutes of traffic, constitutes 1 erlang.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] Carried traffic in erlangs is the average number of concurrent calls measured over a given period (often one hour), while offered traffic is the traffic that would be carried if all call-attempts succeeded.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] How much offered traffic is carried in practice will depend on what happens to unanswered calls when all servers are busy.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The CCITT named the international unit of telephone traffic the erlang in 1946 in honor of Agner Krarup Erlang.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] In Erlang's analysis of efficient telephone line usage, he derived the formulae for two important cases, Erlang-B and Erlang-C, which became foundational results in teletraffic engineering and queueing theory.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] His results, which are still used today, relate quality of service to the number of available servers.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] Both formulae take offered load as one of their main inputs (in erlangs), which is often expressed as call arrival rate times average call length.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] A distinguishing assumption behind the Erlang B formula is that there is no queue, so that if all service elements are already in use then a newly arriving call will be blocked and subsequently lost.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The formula gives the probability of this occurring.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] In contrast, the Erlang C formula provides for the possibility of an unlimited queue and it gives the probability that a new call will need to wait in the queue due to all servers being in use.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] Erlang's formulae apply quite widely, but they may fail when congestion is especially high causing unsuccessful traffic to repeatedly retry.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] One way of accounting for retries when no queue is available is the Extended Erlang B method.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] When used to represent *carried traffic*, a value (which can be a non-integer such as 43.5) followed by "erlangs" represents the average number of concurrent calls carried by the circuits (or other service-providing elements), where that average is calculated over some reasonable period of time.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The period over which the average is calculated is often one hour, but shorter periods (e.g., 15 minutes) may be used where it is known that there are short spurts of demand and a traffic measurement is desired that does not mask these spurts.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] One erlang of carried traffic refers to a single resource being in continuous use, or two channels each being in use fifty percent of the time, and so on.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] For example, if an office has two telephone operators who are both busy all the time, that would represent two erlangs (2 E) of traffic; or a radio channel that is occupied continuously during the period of interest (e.g. one hour) is said to have a load of 1 erlang.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] When used to describe *offered traffic*, a value followed by "erlangs" represents the average number of concurrent calls that would have been carried if there were an unlimited number of circuits (that is, if the call-attempts that were made when all circuits were in use had not been rejected).
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The relationship between offered traffic and carried traffic depends on the design of the system and user behavior.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] Three common models are (a) callers whose call-attempts are rejected go away and never come back, (b) callers whose call-attempts are rejected try again within a fairly short space of time, and (c) the system allows users to wait in queue until a circuit becomes available.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] A third measurement of traffic is *instantaneous traffic*, expressed as a certain number of erlangs, meaning the exact number of calls taking place at a point in time.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] In this case, the number is a non-negative integer.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] Traffic-level-recording devices, such as moving-pen recorders, plot instantaneous traffic.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The concepts and mathematics introduced by Agner Krarup Erlang have broad applicability beyond telephony.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] They apply wherever users arrive more or less at random to receive exclusive service from any one of a group of service-providing elements without prior reservation, for example, where the service-providing elements are ticket-sales windows, toilets on an airplane, or motel rooms.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The goal of Erlang's traffic theory is to determine exactly how many service-providing elements should be provided in order to satisfy users, without wasteful over-provisioning.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] To do this, a target is set for the grade of service (GoS) or quality of service (QoS).
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] For example, in a system where there is no queuing, the GoS may be that no more than 1 call in 100 is blocked (i.e., rejected) due to all circuits being in use (a GoS of 0.01), which becomes the target probability of call blocking, *P*b, when using the Erlang B formula.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] There are several resulting formulae, including Erlang B, Erlang C and the related Engset formula, based on different models of user behavior and system operation.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] These may each be derived by means of a special case of continuous-time Markov processes known as a birth–death process.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The more recent Extended Erlang B method provides a further traffic solution that draws on Erlang's results.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] provided that *h* and *λ* are expressed using the same units of time (seconds and calls per second, or minutes and calls per minute).
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The practical measurement of traffic is typically based on continuous observations over several days or weeks, during which the instantaneous traffic is recorded at regular, short intervals (such as every few seconds).
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] These measurements are then used to calculate a single result, most commonly the busy-hour traffic (in erlangs).
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] This is the average number of concurrent calls during a given one-hour period of the day, where that period is selected to give the highest result.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] (This result is called the time-consistent busy-hour traffic).
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] An alternative is to calculate a busy-hour traffic value separately for each day (which may correspond to slightly different times each day) and take the average of these values.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] This generally gives a slightly higher value than the time-consistent busy-hour value.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] Where the existing busy-hour carried traffic, *E*c, is measured on an already overloaded system, with a significant level of blocking, it is necessary to take account of the blocked calls in estimating the busy-hour offered traffic *E*o (which is the traffic value to be used in the Erlang formulae).
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The offered traffic can be estimated by *E*o = *E*c/(1 − *P*b).
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] For this purpose, where the system includes a means of counting blocked calls and successful calls, *P*b can be estimated directly from the proportion of calls that are blocked.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] Failing that, *P*b can be estimated by using *E*c in place of *E*o in the Erlang formula and the resulting estimate of *P*b can then be used in *E*o = *E*c/(1 − *P*b) to provide a first estimate of *E*o.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] Another method of estimating *E*o in an overloaded system is to measure the busy-hour call arrival rate, *λ* (counting successful calls and blocked calls), and the average call-holding time (for successful calls), *h*, and then estimate *E*o using the formula *E* = *λh*.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] For a situation where the traffic to be handled is completely new traffic, the only choice is to try to model expected user behavior.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] A projection of busy-hour offered traffic would then be *E*o = ⁠*NUC*/60⁠*h* erlangs.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] It is, for example, used to dimension a telephone network's links.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The formula was derived by Agner Krarup Erlang and is not limited to telephone networks, since it describes a probability in a queuing system (albeit a special case with a number of servers but no queueing space for incoming calls to wait for a free server).
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] Hence, the formula is also used in certain inventory systems with lost sales.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The formula applies under the condition that an unsuccessful call, because the line is busy, is not queued or retried, but instead really vanishes forever.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] It is assumed that call attempts arrive following a Poisson process, so call arrival instants are independent.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] Further, it is assumed that the message lengths (holding times) are exponentially distributed (Markovian system), although the formula turns out to apply under general holding time distributions.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The Erlang B formula assumes an infinite population of sources (such as telephone subscribers), which jointly offer traffic to *N* servers (such as telephone lines).
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The rate expressing the frequency at which new calls arrive, λ, (birth rate, traffic intensity, etc.) is constant, and does *not* depend on the number of active sources.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The total number of sources is assumed to be infinite.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The Erlang B formula calculates the blocking probability of a buffer-less loss system, where a request that is not served immediately is aborted, causing that no requests become queued.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] Blocking occurs when a new request arrives at a time where all available servers are currently busy.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The formula also assumes that blocked traffic is cleared and does not return.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The *erlang* is a dimensionless load unit calculated as the mean arrival rate, *λ*, multiplied by the mean call holding time, *h*.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The unit has to be dimensionless for Little's Law to be dimensionally sane.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The recursive form is derivable from the non-recursive form by repeated substitution.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The Erlang B formula is decreasing and convex in *m*.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] It requires that call arrivals can be modeled by a Poisson process, which is not always a good match, but is valid for any statistical distribution of call holding times with a finite mean.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] It applies to traffic transmission systems that do not buffer traffic.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] More modern examples compared to POTS where Erlang B is still applicable, are optical burst switching (OBS) and several current approaches to optical packet switching (OPS).
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] Erlang B was developed as a trunk sizing tool for telephone networks with holding times in the minutes range, but being a mathematical equation it applies on any time-scale.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The steps in the process are as follows.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] It starts at iteration $k=0$ with a known initial baseline level of traffic $E_{0}$ , which is successively adjusted to calculate a sequence of new offered traffic values $E_{k+1}$ , each of which accounts for the recalls arising from the previously calculated offered traffic $E_{k}$ .
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] Calculate the new offered traffic $E_{k+1}=E_{0}+R$ where $E_{0}$ is the initial (baseline) level of traffic.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] Return to step 1, substituting $E_{k+1}$ for $E_{k}$ , and iterate until a stable value of E is obtained.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] Once a satisfactory value of E has been found, the blocking probability $P_{\text{b}}$ and the recall factor can be used to calculate the probability that all of a caller's attempts are lost, not just their first call but also any subsequent retries.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] The *Erlang C formula* expresses the probability that an arriving customer will need to queue (as opposed to immediately being served).
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] Just as the Erlang B formula, Erlang C assumes an infinite population of sources, which jointly offer traffic of E erlangs to m servers.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] However, if all the servers are busy when a request arrives from a source, the request is queued.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] An unlimited number of requests may be held in the queue in this way simultaneously.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] This formula calculates the probability of queuing offered traffic, assuming that blocked calls stay in the system until they can be handled.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] This formula is used to determine the number of agents or customer service representatives needed to staff a call centre, for a specified desired probability of queuing.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] However, the Erlang C formula assumes that callers never hang up while in queue, which makes the formula predict that more agents should be used than are really needed to maintain a desired service level.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] It is assumed that the call arrivals can be modeled by a Poisson process and that call holding times are described by an exponential distribution, therefore the Erlang C formula follows from the assumptions of the M/M/c queue model.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] When Erlang developed the Erlang-B and Erlang-C traffic equations, they were developed on a set of assumptions.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] These assumptions are accurate under most conditions; however in the event of extremely high traffic congestion, Erlang's equations fail to accurately predict the correct number of circuits required because of re-entrant traffic.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] This is termed a *high-loss system*, where congestion breeds further congestion at peak times.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] In such cases, it is first necessary for many additional circuits to be made available so that the high loss can be alleviated.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] Once this action has been taken, congestion will return to reasonable levels and Erlang's equations can then be used to determine how exactly many circuits are really required.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] An example of an instance which would cause such a High Loss System to develop would be if a TV-based advertisement were to announce a particular telephone number to call at a specific time.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] In this case, a large number of people would simultaneously phone the number provided.
[src:queueing-theory/erlang-unit] If the service provider had not catered for this sudden peak demand, extreme traffic congestion will develop and Erlang's equations cannot be used.
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] In queueing theory, a discipline within the mathematical theory of probability, **Kendall's notation** (or sometimes **Kendall notation**) is the standard system used to describe and classify a queueing node.
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] Kendall proposed describing queueing models using three factors written A/S/*c* in 1953 where A denotes the time between arrivals to the queue, S the service time distribution and *c* the number of service channels open at the node.
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] It has since been extended to A/S/*c*/*K*/*N*/D where *K* is the capacity of the queue, *N* is the size of the population of jobs to be served, and D is the queueing discipline.
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] When the final three parameters are not specified (e.g.
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] M/M/1 queue), it is assumed *K* = ∞, *N* = ∞ and D = FIFO.
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] A M/M/1 queue means that the time between arrivals is Markovian (M), i.e. the inter-arrival time follows an exponential distribution of parameter λ.
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] The second M means that the service time is Markovian: it follows an exponential distribution of parameter μ.
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] The last parameter is the number of service channel, which is one (1).
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] In this section, we describe the parameters A/S/*c*/*K*/*N*/D from left to right.
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] This gives the distribution of time of the service of a customer.
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] The number of service channels (or servers).
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] The M/M/1 queue has a single server and the M/M/c queue *c* servers.
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] The capacity of queue, or the maximum number of customers allowed in the queue.
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] When the number is at this maximum, further arrivals are turned away.
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] If this number is omitted, the capacity is assumed to be unlimited, or infinite.
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] The size of the population from which the customers come.
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] A small population will significantly affect the effective arrival rate, because, as more customers are in system, there are fewer free customers available to arrive into the system.
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] If this number is omitted, the population is assumed to be unlimited, or infinite.
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] : An alternative notation practice is to record the queue discipline before the population and system capacity, with or without enclosing parenthesis.
[src:queueing-theory/kendall-s-notation] This does not normally cause confusion because the notation is different.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] The relationship is not influenced by the arrival process distribution, the service distribution, the service order, or practically anything else.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] In most queuing systems, service time is the bottleneck that creates the queue.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] The result applies to any system, and particularly, it applies to systems within systems.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] For example in a bank branch, the customer line might be one subsystem, and each of the tellers another subsystem, and Little's result could be applied to each one, as well as the whole thing.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] The only requirement is that the system be ergodic.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] In some cases it is possible not only to mathematically relate the *average* number in the system to the *average* wait but even to relate the entire *probability distribution* (and moments) of the number in the system to the wait.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] In a 1954 paper, Little's law was assumed true and used without proof.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] The form *L* = *λW* was first published by Philip M.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] Morse where he challenged readers to find a situation where the relationship did not hold.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] Little published in 1961 his proof of the law, showing that no such situation existed.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] Little's proof was followed by a simpler version by Jewell and another by Eilon.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] Shaler Stidham published a different and more intuitive proof in 1972.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] Imagine an application that had no easy way to measure response time.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] For example: A queue depth meter shows an average of nine jobs waiting to be serviced.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] Add one for the job being serviced, so there is an average of ten jobs in the system.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] Another meter shows a mean throughput of 50 per second.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] The mean response time is calculated as 0.2 seconds = 10 / 50 per second.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] Imagine a small store with a single counter and an area for browsing, where only one person can be at the counter at a time, and no one leaves without buying something.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] If the rate at which people enter the store (called the arrival rate) is the rate at which they exit (called the exit rate), the system is stable.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] By contrast, an arrival rate exceeding an exit rate would represent an unstable system, where the number of waiting customers in the store would gradually increase towards infinity.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] Assume customers arrive at the rate of 10 per hour and stay an average of 0.5 hour.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] This means we should find the average number of customers in the store at any time to be 5.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] Now suppose the store is considering doing more advertising to raise the arrival rate to 20 per hour.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] The store must either be prepared to host an average of 10 occupants or must reduce the time each customer spends in the store to 0.25 hour.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] The store might achieve the latter by ringing up the bill faster or by adding more counters.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] We can apply Little's Law to systems within the store.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] For example, consider the counter and its queue.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] Assume we notice that there are on average 2 customers in the queue and at the counter.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] We know the arrival rate is 10 per hour, so customers must be spending 0.2 hours on average checking out.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] We can even apply Little's Law to the counter itself.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] The average number of people at the counter would be in the range (0, 1) since no more than one person can be at the counter at a time.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] In that case, the average number of people at the counter is also known as the utilisation of the counter.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] However, because a store in reality generally has a limited amount of space, it can eventually become unstable.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] If the arrival rate is much greater than the exit rate, the store will eventually start to overflow, and thus any new arriving customers will simply be rejected (and forced to go somewhere else or try again later) until there is once again free space available in the store.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] This is also the difference between the *arrival rate* and the *effective arrival rate*, where the arrival rate roughly corresponds to the rate at which customers arrive at the store, whereas the effective arrival rate corresponds to the rate at which customers *enter* the store.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] However, in a system with an infinite size and no loss, the two are equal.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] Little's law is widely used in manufacturing to predict lead time based on the production rate and the amount of work-in-process.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] Software-performance testers have used Little's law to ensure that the observed performance results are not due to bottlenecks imposed by the testing apparatus.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] Other applications include staffing emergency departments in hospitals.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] Lastly, an equivalent version of Little's law also applies in the fields of demography and population biology, although not referred to as "Little's Law".
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] For example, Cohen (2008) explains that in a homogeneous stationary population without migration, $P=B\times e$ , where P is the total population size, B is the number of births per year, and e is the life expectancy from birth.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] The formula $P=B\times e$ is thus directly equivalent to Little's law ( $L=\lambda \times W$ ).
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] However, biological populations tend to be dynamic and therefore more complicated to model accurately.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] In some cases, it is possible not only to relate averages but to relate the entire probability distribution of the number in the system to the time in the system under a first come, first served discipline.
[src:queueing-theory/little-s-law] A distributional relation for many FIFO/Poisson-class systems was derived by Keilson and Servi (1988) and further developed in related work, including links to the Fuhrmann–Cooper decomposition; later, Bertsimas and Nakazato (1995) provided a new proof and surveyed applications.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] In queueing theory, a discipline within the mathematical theory of probability, an **M/M/1 queue** represents the queue length in a system having a single server, where arrivals are determined by a Poisson process and job service times have an exponential distribution.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] The model name is written in Kendall's notation.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] The model is the most elementary of queueing models and an attractive object of study as closed-form expressions can be obtained for many metrics of interest in this model.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] An extension of this model with more than one server is the M/M/c queue.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] An M/M/1 queue is a stochastic process whose state space is the set {0,1,2,3,...} where the value corresponds to the number of customers in the system, including any currently in service.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] This is the same continuous time Markov chain as in a birth–death process.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] The state space diagram for this chain is as below.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] The model is considered stable only if λ < μ.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] If, on average, arrivals happen faster than service completions the queue will grow indefinitely long and the system will not have a stationary distribution.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] The stationary distribution is the limiting distribution for large values of *t*.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] Various performance measures can be computed explicitly for the M/M/1 queue.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] We write ρ = λ/μ for the utilization of the buffer and require ρ < 1 for the queue to be stable. ρ represents the average proportion of time which the server is occupied.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] We see that the number of customers in the system is geometrically distributed with parameter 1 − *ρ*.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] Thus the average number of customers in the system is *ρ*/(1 − *ρ*) and the variance of number of customers in the system is *ρ*/(1 − *ρ*)2.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] This result holds for any work conserving service regime, such as processor sharing.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] The busy period is the time period measured between the instant a customer arrives to an empty system until the instant a customer departs leaving behind an empty system.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] where *I*1 is a modified Bessel function of the first kind, obtained by using Laplace transforms and inverting the solution.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] The average response time or sojourn time (total time a customer spends in the system) does not depend on scheduling discipline and can be computed using Little's law as 1/(*μ* − *λ*).
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] The distribution of response times experienced does depend on scheduling discipline.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] In an M/M/1-PS queue there is no waiting line and all jobs receive an equal proportion of the service capacity.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] Suppose the single server serves at rate 16 and there are 4 jobs in the system, each job will experience service at rate 4.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] The rate at which jobs receive service changes each time a job arrives at or departs from the system.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] For customers who arrive to find the queue as a stationary process, the Laplace transform of the distribution of response times experienced by customers was published in 1970, for which an integral representation is known.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] The mean response time for a job arriving and requiring amount *x* of service can therefore be computed as *x μ*/(*μ* − *λ*).
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] An alternative approach computes the same results using a spectral expansion method.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] We can write a probability mass function dependent on *t* to describe the probability that the M/M/1 queue is in a particular state at a given time.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] We assume that the queue is initially in state *i* and write *p**k*(*t*) for the probability of being in state *k* at time *t*.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] where i is the initial number of customers in the station at time $t=0$ , $\rho =\lambda /\mu$ , $a=2{\sqrt {\lambda \mu }}$ and $I_{k}$ is the modified Bessel function of the first kind.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] Moments for the transient solution can be expressed as the sum of two monotone functions.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] When the utilization *ρ* is close to 1 the process can be approximated by a reflected Brownian motion with drift parameter *λ* – *μ* and variance parameter *λ* + *μ*.
[src:queueing-theory/m-1-queue] This heavy traffic limit was first introduced by John Kingman.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] It can also be used for the number of events in other types of intervals than time, and in dimension greater than 1 (e.g., number of events in a given area or volume).
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The Poisson distribution is named after French mathematician Siméon Denis Poisson.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] It plays an important role for discrete-stable distributions.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Under a Poisson distribution with the expectation of λ events in a given interval, the probability of k events in the same interval is: ${\frac {\lambda ^{k}e^{-\lambda }}{k!}}.$ For instance, consider a call center which receives an average of *λ* = 3 calls per minute at all times of day.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] If the number of calls received in any two given disjoint time intervals is independent, then the number k of calls received during any minute has a Poisson probability distribution.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Receiving *k* = 1 to 4 calls then has a probability of about 0.77, while receiving 0 or at least 5 calls has a probability of about 0.23.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] A classic example used to motivate the Poisson distribution is the number of radioactive decay events during a fixed observation period.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The introduction of the Poisson distribution is credited to French mathematician and physicist Siméon Denis Poisson (1781–1840), who published it together with his probability theory in *Recherches sur la probabilité des jugements en matière criminelle et en matière civile* (1837).
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] This work theorizes about the number of wrongful convictions in a given country by focusing on certain random variables N that count the number of events that take place during a time interval of given length.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] However, similar results had already been given in 1711 by Abraham de Moivre in *De Mensura Sortis seu; de Probabilitate Eventuum in Ludis a Casu Fortuito Pendentibus* .
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] This makes it an example of Stigler's law and it has prompted some authors to argue that the Poisson distribution should bear the name of de Moivre.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] In 1860, Simon Newcomb fitted the Poisson distribution to the number of stars found in a unit of space.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] A further practical application was made by Ladislaus Bortkiewicz in 1898.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Bortkiewicz showed that the frequency with which soldiers in the Prussian army were accidentally killed by horse kicks could be well modeled by a Poisson distribution..
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The Poisson distribution can be applied to systems with a large number of possible events, each of which is rare.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The number of such events that occur during a fixed time interval is, under the right circumstances, a random number with a Poisson distribution.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The equation can be adapted if, instead of the average number of events $\lambda ,$ we are given the average rate r at which events occur.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Examples of the occurrence of random points in space are: the locations of asteroid impacts with earth (2-dimensional), the locations of imperfections in a material (3-dimensional), and the locations of trees in a forest (2-dimensional).
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] If these conditions are true, then k is a Poisson random variable; the distribution of k is a Poisson distribution.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The number of students who arrive at the student union per minute will likely not follow a Poisson distribution, because the rate is not constant (low rate during class time, high rate between class times) and the arrivals of individual students are not independent (students tend to come in groups).
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The non-constant arrival rate may be modeled as a mixed Poisson distribution, and the arrival of groups rather than individual students as a compound Poisson process.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The number of magnitude 5 earthquakes per year in a country may not follow a Poisson distribution if one large earthquake increases the probability of aftershocks of similar magnitude.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Examples in which at least one event is guaranteed are not Poisson distributed; but may be modeled using a zero-truncated Poisson distribution.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Count distributions in which the number of intervals with zero events is higher than predicted by a Poisson model may be modeled using a zero-inflated model.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The higher non-centered moments *m**k* of the Poisson distribution are Touchard polynomials in λ: $m_{k}=\sum _{i=0}^{k}\lambda ^{i}{\begin{Bmatrix}k\\i\end{Bmatrix}},$ where the braces { } denote Stirling numbers of the second kind.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] In other words, $E[X]=\lambda ,\quad E[X(X-1)]=\lambda ^{2},\quad E[X(X-1)(X-2)]=\lambda ^{3},\cdots$ When the expected value is set to *λ* = 1, Dobinski's formula implies that the n‑th moment is equal to the number of partitions of a set of size n.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] It is a maximum-entropy distribution among the set of generalized binomial distributions $B_{n}(\lambda )$ with mean $\lambda$ and $n\to \infty$ , where a generalized binomial distribution is defined as a distribution of the sum of N independent but not identically distributed Bernoulli variables.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The upper bound is proved using a standard Chernoff bound.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Further noting that $X+Y\sim \operatorname {Pois} (\lambda +\mu ),$ and computing a lower bound on the unconditional probability gives the result.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] More details can be found in the appendix of Kamath et al.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The Poisson distribution can be derived as a limiting case to the binomial distribution as the number of trials goes to infinity and the expected number of successes remains fixed — see law of rare events below.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Therefore, it can be used as an approximation of the binomial distribution if n is sufficiently large and p is sufficiently small.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The Poisson distribution is a good approximation of the binomial distribution if n is at least 20 and p is smaller than or equal to 0.05, and an excellent approximation if *n* ≥ 100 and *np* ≤ 10.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Letting $F_{\mathrm {B} }$ and $F_{\mathrm {P} }$ be the respective cumulative density functions of the binomial and Poisson distributions, one has: $F_{\mathrm {B} }(k;n,p)\ \approx \ F_{\mathrm {P} }(k;\lambda =np).$ One derivation of this uses probability-generating functions.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Consider a Bernoulli trial (coin-flip) whose probability of one success (or expected number of successes) is $\lambda \leq 1$ within a given interval.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Split the interval into n parts, and perform a trial in each subinterval with probability ${\tfrac {\lambda }{n}}$ .
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The factor of $e{\sqrt {m}}$ can be replaced by 2 if f is further assumed to be monotonically increasing or decreasing.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] This distribution has been extended to the bivariate case.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The free Poisson distribution with jump size $\alpha$ and rate $\lambda$ arises in free probability theory as the limit of repeated free convolution $\left(\left(1-{\frac {\lambda }{N}}\right)\delta _{0}+{\frac {\lambda }{N}}\delta _{\alpha }\right)^{\boxplus N}$ as *N* → ∞.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] In other words, let $X_{N}$ be random variables so that $X_{N}$ has value $\alpha$ with probability ${\textstyle {\frac {\lambda }{N}}}$ and value 0 with the remaining probability.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Assume also that the family $X_{1},X_{2},\ldots$ are freely independent.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] This definition is analogous to one of the ways in which the classical Poisson distribution is obtained from a (classical) Poisson process.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] This law also arises in random matrix theory as the Marchenko–Pastur law.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] We give values of some important transforms of the free Poisson law; the computation can be found in e.g. in the book *Lectures on the Combinatorics of Free Probability* by A.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Given a sample of n measured values $k_{i}\in \{0,1,\dots \},$ for *i* = 1, ..., *n*, we wish to estimate the value of the parameter λ of the Poisson population from which the sample was drawn.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Since each observation has expectation λ, so does the sample mean.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Therefore, the maximum likelihood estimate is an unbiased estimator of λ.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] It is also an efficient estimator since its variance achieves the Cramér–Rao lower bound (CRLB).
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Also it can be proven that the sum (and hence the sample mean as it is a one-to-one function of the sum) is a complete and sufficient statistic for λ.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] To prove sufficiency we may use the factorization theorem.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The first term $h(\mathbf {x} )$ depends only on $\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The second term $g(T(\mathbf {x} )|\lambda )$ depends on the sample only through ${\textstyle T(\mathbf {x} )=\sum _{i=1}^{n}x_{i}.}$ Thus, $T(\mathbf {x} )$ is sufficient.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] So λ is the average of the *k**i* values.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Obtaining the sign of the second derivative of L at the stationary point will determine what kind of extreme value λ is.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] which is the negative of n times the reciprocal of the average of the *k**i*.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] This expression is negative when the average is positive.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] If this is satisfied, then the stationary point maximizes the probability function.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] For this equality to hold, $g(t)$ must be 0.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] This follows from the fact that none of the other terms will be 0 for all t in the sum and for all possible values of $\lambda .$ Hence, $E(g(T))=0$ for all $\lambda$ implies that $P_{\lambda }(g(T)=0)=1,$ and the statistic has been shown to be complete.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The confidence interval for the mean of a Poisson distribution can be expressed using the relationship between the cumulative distribution functions of the Poisson and chi-squared distributions.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The chi-squared distribution is itself closely related to the gamma distribution, and this leads to an alternative expression.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] where $\chi ^{2}(p;n)$ is the quantile function (corresponding to a lower tail area p) of the chi-squared distribution with n degrees of freedom and $F^{-1}(p;n,1)$ is the quantile function of a gamma distribution with shape parameter n and scale parameter 1.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] This interval is 'exact' in the sense that its coverage probability is never less than the nominal 1 – *α*.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] $k=\sum _{i=1}^{n}k_{i},$ calculate an interval for *μ* = *nλ*, and then derive the interval for λ.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] In Bayesian inference, the conjugate prior for the rate parameter λ of the Poisson distribution is the gamma distribution.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Note that the posterior mean is linear and is given by $E[\lambda \mid k_{1},\ldots ,k_{n}]={\frac {\alpha +\sum _{i=1}^{n}k_{i}}{\beta +n}}.$ It can be shown that gamma distribution is the only prior that induces linearity of the conditional mean.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Moreover, a converse result exists which states that if the conditional mean is close to a linear function in the $L_{2}$ distance than the prior distribution of λ must be close to gamma distribution in Levy distance.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The posterior mean E[*λ*] approaches the maximum likelihood estimate ${\widehat {\lambda }}_{\mathrm {MLE} }$ in the limit as $\alpha \to 0,\beta \to 0,$ which follows immediately from the general expression of the mean of the gamma distribution.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The posterior predictive distribution for a single additional observation is a negative binomial distribution, sometimes called a gamma–Poisson distribution.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Suppose $X_{1},X_{2},\dots ,X_{p}$ is a set of independent random variables from a set of p Poisson distributions, each with a parameter $\lambda _{i},$ $i=1,\dots ,p,$ and we would like to estimate these parameters.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] In probabilistic number theory, Gallagher showed in 1976 that, if a certain version of the unproved prime r-tuple conjecture holds, then the counts of prime numbers in short intervals would obey a Poisson distribution.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The rate of an event is related to the probability of an event occurring in some small subinterval (of time, space or otherwise).
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] In the case of the Poisson distribution, one assumes that there exists a small enough subinterval for which the probability of an event occurring twice is "negligible".
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] With this assumption one can derive the Poisson distribution from the binomial one, given only the information of expected number of total events in the whole interval.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Let the total number of events in the whole interval be denoted by $\lambda .$ Divide the whole interval into n subintervals $I_{1},\dots ,I_{n}$ of equal size, such that $n>\lambda$ (since we are interested in only very small portions of the interval this assumption is meaningful).
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Hence for each subdivision of the interval we have approximated the occurrence of the event as a Bernoulli process of the form ${\textrm {B}}(n,\lambda /n).$ As we have noted before we want to consider only very small subintervals.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Therefore, we take the limit as n goes to infinity.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] In this case the binomial distribution converges to what is known as the Poisson distribution by the Poisson limit theorem.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] In such cases n is very large and p is very small (and so the expectation np is of intermediate magnitude).
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] This approximation is sometimes known as the *law of rare events*, since each of the n individual Bernoulli events rarely occurs.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The name "law of rare events" may be misleading because the total count of success events in a Poisson process need not be rare if the parameter np is not small.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The variance of the binomial distribution is 1 − *p* times that of the Poisson distribution, so almost equal when p is very small.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The word *law* is sometimes used as a synonym of probability distribution, and *convergence in law* means *convergence in distribution*.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Accordingly, the Poisson distribution is sometimes called the "law of small numbers" because it is the probability distribution of the number of occurrences of an event that happens rarely but has very many opportunities to happen.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] *The Law of Small Numbers* is a book by Ladislaus Bortkiewicz about the Poisson distribution, published in 1898.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The Poisson distribution arises as the number of points of a Poisson point process located in some finite region.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Poisson regression and negative binomial regression are useful for analyses where the dependent (response) variable is the count (0, 1, 2, ... ) of the number of events or occurrences in an interval.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The Luria–Delbrück experiment tested against the hypothesis of Lamarckian evolution, which should result in a Poisson distribution.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Katz and Miledi measured the membrane potential with and without the presence of acetylcholine (ACh).
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] When ACh is present, ion channels on the membrane would be open randomly at a small fraction of the time.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] As there are a large number of ion channels each open for a small fraction of the time, the total number of ion channels open at any moment is Poisson distributed.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] When ACh is not present, effectively no ion channels are open.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Subtracting the effect of noise, Katz and Miledi found the mean and variance of membrane potential to be $8.5\times 10^{-3}\;\mathrm {V}$ and $(29.2\times 10^{-6}\;\mathrm {V} )^{2}$ respectively, giving $V_{\text{ion}}=10^{-7}\;\mathrm {V}$ .
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] During each cellular replication event, the number of mutations is roughly Poisson distributed.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] For example, the HIV virus has 10,000 base pairs, and has a mutation rate of about 1 per 30,000 base pairs, meaning the number of mutations per replication event is distributed as $\mathrm {Pois} (1/3)$ .
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] In a Poisson process, the number of observed occurrences fluctuates about its mean λ with a standard deviation $\sigma _{k}={\sqrt {\lambda }}.$ These fluctuations are denoted as *Poisson noise* or (particularly in electronics) as *shot noise*.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The correlation of the mean and standard deviation in counting independent discrete occurrences is useful scientifically.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] By monitoring how the fluctuations vary with the mean signal, one can estimate the contribution of a single occurrence, *even if that contribution is too small to be detected directly*.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] For example, the charge e on an electron can be estimated by correlating the magnitude of an electric current with its shot noise.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] An everyday example is the graininess that appears as photographs are enlarged; the graininess is due to Poisson fluctuations in the number of reduced silver grains, not to the individual grains themselves.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] By correlating the graininess with the degree of enlargement, one can estimate the contribution of an individual grain (which is otherwise too small to be seen unaided).
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] In causal set theory the discrete elements of spacetime follow a Poisson distribution in the volume.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The Poisson distribution also appears in quantum mechanics, especially quantum optics.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Namely, for a quantum harmonic oscillator system in a coherent state, the probability of measuring a particular energy level has a Poisson distribution.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The Poisson distribution poses two different tasks for dedicated software libraries: *evaluating* the distribution $P(k;\lambda )$ , and *drawing random numbers* according to that distribution.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Computing $P(k;\lambda )$ for given k and $\lambda$ is a trivial task that can be accomplished by using the standard definition of $P(k;\lambda )$ in terms of exponential, power, and factorial functions.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] However, the conventional definition of the Poisson distribution contains two terms that can easily overflow on computers: *λ**k* and *k*!.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The fraction of *λ**k* to *k*! can also produce a rounding error that is very large compared to *e*−*λ*, and therefore give an erroneous result.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] For numerical stability the Poisson probability mass function should therefore be evaluated as $\!f(k;\lambda )=\exp \left[k\ln \lambda -\lambda -\ln \Gamma (k+1)\right],$ which is mathematically equivalent but numerically stable.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The natural logarithm of the Gamma function can be obtained using the `lgamma` function in the C standard library (C99 version) or R, the `gammaln` function in MATLAB or SciPy, or the `log_gamma` function in Fortran 2008 and later.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The complexity is linear in the returned value k, which is λ on average.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] There are many other algorithms to improve this.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Some are given in Ahrens & Dieter, see § References below.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] For large values of λ, the value of *L* = *e*−*λ* may be so small that it is hard to represent.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] The choice of STEP depends on the threshold of overflow.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] For double precision floating point format the threshold is near *e*700, so 500 should be a safe *STEP*.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Other solutions for large values of λ include rejection sampling and using Gaussian approximation.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Inverse transform sampling is simple and efficient for small values of λ, and requires only one uniform random number u per sample.
[src:queueing-theory/poisson-distribution] Cumulative probabilities are examined in turn until one exceeds u.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Queueing theory has its origins in research by Agner Krarup Erlang, who created models to describe the system of incoming calls at the Copenhagen Telephone Exchange Company.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] These ideas were seminal to the field of teletraffic engineering and have since seen applications in telecommunications, traffic engineering, computing, project management, and particularly industrial engineering, where they are applied in the design of factories, shops, offices, and hospitals.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Queueing theory is one of the major areas of study in the discipline of management science.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Through management science, businesses are able to solve a variety of problems using different scientific and mathematical approaches.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Queueing analysis is the probabilistic analysis of waiting lines, and thus the results, also referred to as the operating characteristics, are probabilistic rather than deterministic.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The overall goal of queueing analysis is to compute these characteristics for the current system and then test several alternatives that could lead to improvement.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Computing the operating characteristics for the current system and comparing the values to the characteristics of the alternative systems allows managers to see the pros and cons of each potential option.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] These systems help in the final decision making process by showing ways to increase savings, reduce waiting time, improve efficiency, etc.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The main queueing models that can be used are the single-server waiting line system and the multiple-server waiting line system, which are discussed further below.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] These models can be further differentiated depending on whether service times are constant or undefined, the queue length is finite, the calling population is finite, etc.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] A *queue* or *queueing node* can be thought of as nearly a black box.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] *Jobs* (also called *customers* or *requests*, depending on the field) arrive to the queue, possibly wait some time, take some time being processed, and then depart from the queue.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] However, the queueing node is not quite a pure black box since some information is needed about the inside of the queueing node.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The queue has one or more *servers* which can each be paired with an arriving job.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] When the job is completed and departs, that server will again be free to be paired with another arriving job.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] An analogy often used is that of the cashier at a supermarket.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Customers arrive, are processed by the cashier, and depart.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Each cashier processes one customer at a time, and hence this is a queueing node with only one server.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] A setting where a customer will leave immediately if the cashier is busy when the customer arrives, is referred to as a queue with no *buffer* (or no *waiting area*).
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] A setting with a waiting zone for up to *n* customers is called a queue with a buffer of size *n*.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The behaviour of a single queue (also called a *queueing node*) can be described by a birth–death process, which describes the arrivals and departures from the queue, along with the number of jobs currently in the system.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] If *k* denotes the number of jobs in the system (either being serviced or waiting if the queue has a buffer of waiting jobs), then an arrival increases *k* by 1 and a departure decreases *k* by 1.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The system transitions between values of *k* by *births* and *deaths*, which occur at the arrival rates $\lambda _{i}$ and the departure rates $\mu _{i}$ for each job i .
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] For a queue, these rates are generally considered not to vary with the number of jobs in the queue, so a single average rate of arrivals/departures per unit time is assumed.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The steady state equations for the birth-and-death process, known as the balance equations, are as follows.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Here $P_{n}$ denotes the steady state probability to be in state *n*.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] which, together with the equation for $P_{n}$ $(n\geq 1)$ , fully describes the required steady state probabilities.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Single queueing nodes are usually described using Kendall's notation in the form A/S/*c* where *A* describes the distribution of durations between each arrival to the queue, *S* the distribution of service times for jobs, and *c* the number of servers at the node.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] For an example of the notation, the M/M/1 queue is a simple model where a single server serves jobs that arrive according to a Poisson process (where inter-arrival durations are exponentially distributed) and have exponentially distributed service times (the M denotes a Markov process).
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] In an M/G/1 queue, the G stands for *general* and indicates an arbitrary probability distribution for service times.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Further, let $E_{n}$ represent the number of times the system enters state *n*, and $L_{n}$ represent the number of times the system leaves state *n*.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] That is, the number of times the system leaves a state differs by at most 1 from the number of times it enters that state, since it will either return into that state at some time in the future ( $E_{n}=L_{n}$ ) or not ( $\left\vert E_{n}-L_{n}\right\vert =1$ ).
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] When the system arrives at a steady state, the arrival rate should be equal to the departure rate.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] A common basic queueing system is attributed to Erlang and is a modification of Little's Law.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Assuming an exponential distribution for the rates, the waiting time *W* can be defined as the proportion of arrivals that are served.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The two-stage one-box model is common in epidemiology.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] In 1909, Agner Krarup Erlang, a Danish engineer who worked for the Copenhagen Telephone Exchange, published the first paper on what would now be called queueing theory.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] He modeled the number of telephone calls arriving at an exchange by a Poisson process and solved the M/D/1 queue in 1917 and M/D/*k* queueing model in 1920.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] If the node has more jobs than servers, then jobs will queue and wait for service.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The M/G/1 queue was solved by Felix Pollaczek in 1930, a solution later recast in probabilistic terms by Aleksandr Khinchin and now known as the Pollaczek–Khinchine formula.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] After the 1940s, queueing theory became an area of research interest to mathematicians.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] In 1953, David George Kendall solved the GI/M/*k* queue and introduced the modern notation for queues, now known as Kendall's notation.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] In 1957, Pollaczek studied the GI/G/1 using an integral equation.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] John Kingman gave a formula for the mean waiting time in a G/G/1 queue, now known as Kingman's formula.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Leonard Kleinrock worked on the application of queueing theory to message switching in the early 1960s and packet switching in the early 1970s.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] His initial contribution to this field was his doctoral thesis at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in 1962, published in book form in 1964.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] His theoretical work published in the early 1970s underpinned the use of packet switching in the ARPANET, a forerunner to the Internet.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The matrix geometric method and matrix analytic methods have allowed queues with phase-type distributed inter-arrival and service time distributions to be considered.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Systems with coupled orbits are an important part in queueing theory in the application to wireless networks and signal processing.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Modern day application of queueing theory concerns among other things product development where (material) products have a spatiotemporal existence, in the sense that products have a certain volume and a certain duration.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Problems such as performance metrics for the M/G/*k* queue remain an open problem.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] this principle states that customers are served one at a time and that the customer that has been waiting the longest is served first.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Service capacity is shared equally between customers.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] (ROS), this discipline states that the next job served is selected at random from the jobs waiting in the queue.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Customers with high priority are served first.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] (where a job in service can be interrupted by a higher-priority job).
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The next job to be served is the one with the smallest size.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The next job to be served is the one with the smallest original size.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The next job to serve is the one with the smallest remaining processing requirement.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Server failures occur according to a stochastic (random) process (usually Poisson) and are followed by setup periods during which the server is unavailable.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The interrupted customer remains in the service area until server is fixed.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Arriving customers not served (either due to the queue having no buffer, or due to balking or reneging by the customer) are also known as *dropouts*.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The average rate of dropouts is a significant parameter describing a queue.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Queue networks are systems in which multiple queues are connected by *customer routing*.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] When a customer is serviced at one node, it can join another node and queue for service, or leave the network.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] For networks of *m* nodes, the state of the system can be described by an *m*–dimensional vector (*x*1, *x*2, ..., *x**m*) where *x**i* represents the number of customers at each node.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The simplest non-trivial networks of queues are called tandem queues.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The first significant results in this area were Jackson networks, for which an efficient product-form stationary distribution exists and the mean value analysis (which allows average metrics such as throughput and sojourn times) can be computed.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] If the total number of customers in the network remains constant, the network is called a *closed network* and has been shown to also have a product–form stationary distribution by the Gordon–Newell theorem.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] This result was extended to the BCMP network, where a network with very general service time, regimes, and customer routing is shown to also exhibit a product–form stationary distribution.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The normalizing constant can be calculated with the Buzen's algorithm, proposed in 1973.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Networks of customers have also been investigated, such as Kelly networks, where customers of different classes experience different priority levels at different service nodes.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Another type of network are G-networks, first proposed by Erol Gelenbe in 1993: these networks do not assume exponential time distributions like the classic Jackson network.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] In discrete-time networks where there is a constraint on which service nodes can be active at any time, the max-weight scheduling algorithm chooses a service policy to give optimal throughput in the case that each job visits only a single-person service node.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] In the more general case where jobs can visit more than one node, backpressure routing gives optimal throughput.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] A network scheduler must choose a queueing algorithm, which affects the characteristics of the larger network.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Mean-field models consider the limiting behaviour of the empirical measure (proportion of queues in different states) as the number of queues *m* approaches infinity.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The impact of other queues on any given queue in the network is approximated by a differential equation.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The deterministic model converges to the same stationary distribution as the original model.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] In a system with high occupancy rates (utilisation near 1), a heavy traffic approximation can be used to approximate the queueing length process by a reflected Brownian motion, Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process, or more general diffusion process.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The number of dimensions of the Brownian process is equal to the number of queueing nodes, with the diffusion restricted to the non-negative orthant.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Fluid models are continuous deterministic analogs of queueing networks obtained by taking the limit when the process is scaled in time and space, allowing heterogeneous objects.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] This scaled trajectory converges to a deterministic equation which allows the stability of the system to be proven.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] It is known that a queueing network can be stable but have an unstable fluid limit.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Queueing theory finds widespread application in computer science and information technology.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] In networking, for instance, queues are integral to routers and switches, where packets queue up for transmission.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] By applying queueing theory principles, designers can optimize these systems, ensuring responsive performance and efficient resource utilization.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Beyond the technological realm, queueing theory is relevant to everyday experiences.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Whether waiting in line at a supermarket or for public transportation, understanding the principles of queueing theory provides valuable insights into optimizing these systems for enhanced user satisfaction.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] At some point, everyone will be involved in an aspect of queuing.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] What some may view to be an inconvenience could possibly be the most effective method.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Queueing theory, a discipline rooted in applied mathematics and computer science, is a field dedicated to the study and analysis of queues, or waiting lines, and their implications across a diverse range of applications.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] This theoretical framework has proven instrumental in understanding and optimizing the efficiency of systems characterized by the presence of queues.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The study of queues is essential in contexts such as traffic systems, computer networks, telecommunications, and service operations.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] Queueing theory delves into various foundational concepts, with the arrival process and service process being central.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The arrival process describes the manner in which entities join the queue over time, often modeled using stochastic processes like Poisson processes.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] The efficiency of queueing systems is gauged through key performance metrics.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] These include the average queue length, average wait time, and system throughput.
[src:queueing-theory/queueing-theory] These metrics provide insights into the system's functionality, guiding decisions aimed at enhancing performance and reducing wait times.
